1023  	 	THE UNIQUE IRELAND ISLAND COVER WITH BOTH POSTMASTER GROTE's HANDSTRUCK "4d" (ONE OF 3 KNOWN) & "6d" MARKS; Remarkable 18 Apr. 1861 env. (closed opening-tears at foot & small stain on RH edge both clear of marks) prepaid to "Saranac Hollow, Clinton County, New York", endorsed "Paid" and "via Halifax" in red, having a black double-arc PM5 "IRELAND ISLE/BERMUDA" c.d.s. on the reverse (over-written by addressee's notes); there is also a very fine rare red Ireland Island Handstruck "6d" nicely placed on the front but crossed out in manuscript with a mostly very fine and very rare matching Ireland Island Handstruck "4d" alongside. Only three examples of the Ireland Island Handstruck "4d" have been recorded; the other two being on straightforward Crowned Circle covers to Canada. These 4d, 6d & 1/- marks were only used at the Ireland Island P.O. and are thought to have been produced on the initiative of the Postmaster, D. Grote; they - especially the 4d (3 known) and 1/- (one known) - are the P.H. equivalent of the (rather more expensive) Perot & Grote "Postmasters Stamps" and are just as rare. This exceptional combination of 4d and 6d marks both struck together is unique; the 6d Packet rate was correct to G.B., but the Packet rate to Canada was only 4d, hence the error. The 4d Packet rate was more expensive & slower than ordinary Ship Letters, hence the rarity of 4d mark. Important Exhibition Item; arguably the rarest of all Bermuda Prestamp covers.    	\pound3000
{{auction: Cavendish January 2009, The Geoffrey Osborn Bermuda Collection}}
</p>
