1026  	 	U.S. CIVIL WAR - BLOCKADE RUNNER COVER WITH THE RARE SMALL ST. GEORGES "BERMUDA/A/PAID" P4 C.D.S. (EARLIEST RECORDED DATE); Fine 23 May 1863 env. with original contents headed "Wilmington, N.C." addressed to "Oaks Sulphur Springs, Jefferson Co., M[iss]o[uri]" during the American Civil War (Jefferson had fallen to the Federal forces in 1861, so there was then no direct route from Wilmington); routed via Bermuda, Halifax (N.S.) and Boston, and so carried (under cover to Mr. A. H. Williams in St Georges) on the successful Blockade-runner vessel 'Cornubia' which left Wilmington on 24 May and reached Bermuda on 27 May 1863. The letter with this envelope was then posted from St. Georges on 3 June with a very fine (especially for this rare mark) small red encircled "BERMUDA/A/PAID" of St. Georges (PM4 - the Earliest Known Date of just 13 recorded examples) nicely placed on the front with red crayon "4[d]" and partial black "BOSTON/5" 23 June transit charge-datestamp. The contents - a Wilmington doctor's wife sending the news that the addressee's husband, also a doctor (who had recently volunteered to help treat the Yellow Fever sufferers in the town) had died of the fever himself. Of particular interest is the postscript giving instructions on how to reply; "...must be mailed as follows; 2 envelopes, the inner addressed to Mrs. Alex R. Midway, Wilmington, N.C., C.S.A. The outer to [the name in a different hand - presumably added in transit in Bermuda in case the letter had been captured en route; A.H. Williams Esqr. (via Halifax, N.S.)], St George, Bermuda, who will forward it by some one of our Confederate vessels." [Plus, again in the second handwriting; "It will be necessary to prepay the Postage, I Understand, to insure it reaching Bermuda".] This is a doubly rare cover - it has one of the rarest of all Bermuda's "PAID" marks, and it is is a U.S. Civil War Blockade-runner cover - with superb contents - that was sent successfully via Bermuda from a 'southern' state to a 'northern' state of America. Most recorded Bermuda blockade-runner covers are addressed to Britain, and mailed unpaid; there were none to the US in the Ludington Collection, and none that were prepaid from Bermuda. Highly Important Civil War and Bermuda Exhibition Item.    \pound3000
{{auction: Cavendish January 2009, The Geoffrey Osborn Bermuda Collection}}
</p>
